{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-tsx","path":"/blog/new-gatsby-blog/","result":{"data":{"post":{"html":"<p>Nearly <a href=\"/blog/new-blog/\">3 years ago</a>, I reinvented <a href=\"benmvp.com\">benmvp.com</a> to be my professional-focused blog. For a while, I was writing a lot, mostly working on the <a href=\"/learning-es6-series/\"><em>Learning ES6</em></a> series. I learned so much writing posts for each of the ES6 features. But then towards the end of 2015 and early 2016, I started getting accepted to speak at conferences like <a href=\"/blog/nodevember-2015/\">Nodevember</a>, <a href=\"/blog/nationjs-nodeday-2016/\">NationJS</a>, <a href=\"/blog/ndc-oslo-2016/\">NDC Oslo</a>, <a href=\"/blog/front-porch-austin-2016/\">Front Porch Austin</a> and <a href=\"/blog/nodesummit-2016/\">NodeSummit</a>. I no longer really had time to blog because my time was spent prepping for <a href=\"/speak/\">conference talks</a>. I didn’t even blog in 2017!</p>\n<p>Well, while speaking at various conferences, this new library called <a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Gatsby</a> kept coming up. It’s a highly-performant React-based static site generator. I was used to static site generators because my previous blog was <a href=\"https://jekyllrb.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Jekyll</a>-based (Ruby). All of my blog posts were simple Markdown files, so I didn’t deal with Jekyll too much, but I still wanted to switch over to Gatsby.</p>\n<p>For one, previewing my posts locally before I published live was surprising difficult with Jekyll. I also kind of like the idea of having my blog written in JavaScript &#x26; React. Plus, I’m pretty sure that learning Gatsby will help me at Eventbrite because our design system documentation app is a React app that really should be statically generated. Finally, I really just wanted to update the look and feel of my blog.</p>\n<p>Here’s how it looked before:</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/70f8b9fe20f66a647a0976d7305b5c78/d50e7/previous-blog.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 75.49999999999999%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Screenshot of old benmvp.com\"\n        title=\"Screenshot of old benmvp.com\"\n        src=\"/static/70f8b9fe20f66a647a0976d7305b5c78/5a190/previous-blog.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/70f8b9fe20f66a647a0976d7305b5c78/772e8/previous-blog.png 200w,\n/static/70f8b9fe20f66a647a0976d7305b5c78/e17e5/previous-blog.png 400w,\n/static/70f8b9fe20f66a647a0976d7305b5c78/5a190/previous-blog.png 800w,\n/static/70f8b9fe20f66a647a0976d7305b5c78/c1b63/previous-blog.png 1200w,\n/static/70f8b9fe20f66a647a0976d7305b5c78/29007/previous-blog.png 1600w,\n/static/70f8b9fe20f66a647a0976d7305b5c78/d50e7/previous-blog.png 2280w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>It wasn’t <em>terrible</em>. It was based on a <a href=\"https://github.com/christoga/jekyll-material\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Material design theme for Jekyll</a>. There are tons of Gatsby starter kits, including those for blogs. I chose the one you see now: <a href=\"https://github.com/greglobinski/gatsby-starter-personal-blog\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">gatsby-starter-personal-blog</a>. It has a lot of slick UX coupled with pretty nice visual design.</p>\n<p>The challenge I found with using Gatsby with the starter kit, though, was that I didn’t know where Gatsby ended and where the starter kit started. The kit did <strong>a lot</strong> for me which was great, but when I was running into issues, I could never be sure if it was just bugs in the starter kit (which there were some). In the end, I was able to get it all working to my liking and migrate over posts. I intend to do more cleanup of the code. Hopefully I’ll contribute some of the fixes back to the starter.</p>\n<p>Last thing. For now I will continue to use <a href=\"https://pages.github.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Github Pages</a> because I’m pretty invested in it for all my other repos, but I am making use of <a href=\"https://www.netlify.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Netlify</a> for CI/CD. I’ve set up <a href=\"https://www.netlify.com/blog/2016/07/20/introducing-deploy-previews-in-netlify/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">deploy previews</a> so that when I create a pull request for the blog repo, I’ll be able to see what it looks like in a “production” environment before actually pushing to benmvp.com. Pretty snazzy stuff!</p>","excerpt":"Nearly 3 years ago, I reinvented benmvp.com to be my professional-focused blog. For a while, I was writing a lot, mostly working on the…","timeToRead":2,"wordCount":{"words":445},"fields":{"slug":"/new-gatsby-blog/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"New Gatsby Blog!","shortDescription":null,"tags":null,"category":"General","date":"May 04, 2018","dateIso":"2018-05-04"}},"categoryPosts":{"edges":[{"node":{"id":"7a4064b5-7b86-5450-a00b-466d040be578","frontmatter":{"title":"New Gatsby site!","shortDescription":"Why I decided to redesign benmvp.com from being a blog site to being a site that contains a blog","tags":["gatsby","performance","website"],"date":"April 29, 2020"